==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Serenade
<hw>Ser`e*nade"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>s⟦eacute⟧r⟦eacute⟧nade</ets>, It. <ets>serenata</ets>, probably fr.
L. <ets>serenus</ets> serene (cf. <er>Serene</er>), misunderstood as a
derivative fr. L. <ets>serus</ets> late. Cf.
<er>Soir⟦eacute⟧e</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Music
sung or performed in the open air at nights; -- usually applied to
musical entertainments given in the open air at night, especially by
gentlemen, in a spirit of gallantry, under the windows of ladies.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A piece of music suitable to be performed at such
times.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Serenade</ent>⟦br⟧

